Need for Lambda expression
--------------------------
Java is a Object oriented programming language and which don't have functional programming feature. 
To have functional programming feature, Lambda expression comes into picture.

Objectives of Lambda expression
-------------------------------
1. Functional programming feature
2. Code optimization

Lambda expression
-----------------
Lambda expression is a anonymous function(Nameless function), which doesn't have rerturnType and return any value. 
Also, doesn't have access modifier.

To use Lambda expression
------------------------
Invoking Lambda expression is done by Functional Interface. 
Before Java7, A Interface which contains only ONE abstract method is called as Functional Interface. 
From Java7, a Functional Interface may or may not contains default and static methods along with abstract method.

Default Functional Interfaces in Java
-------------------------------------
1. Runnable -> run() 
2. Callable -> call()
3. Comparable -> compareTo()
4. ActionListener -> actionPerformed()

@FuntionalInterface - This annotation is used to explicitly represent Functional Interface.

Predefined Functional Interface
-------------------------------
1. Predicate
2. Function
3. Consumer
4. Supplier

The above predefined Functional Interfaces are used to invoke the Lambda expression.
Its located inside java.util.function

Predicate
---------
It takes data of any type and return boolean value. It has test() method.
It will be preferred when we have conditional check.

Function
--------
It takes data of any type and return value of any type. It has apply() method.
It will be preferred when we have to perform the operation and return the value.

Consumer
--------
It takes data of any type and doesn't return any value. It has accept() method.
It will be used to print the data.

Supplier
--------
It doesn't take data of any type but return value of any type. It has get() method.
It will be used to get the system properties, date and time.

Function Chaining
-----------------
Function chaining is a process by which we can combine two functions together.
andThen() and compose() are used to perform the function chaining.
andThen() will process the first function first and the second function second.
compose() will process the second function first and the first function second.





 